                                     {
                                         "text":  "#### What Is a Planet?\n\nToday, there is broad consensus on how planets form.\nHowever, the definition of a planet has been updated in recent years: to be considered a planet, an object must be massive enough to become spherical due to its own gravity, orbit a star, and clear its orbital path of other nearby objects (<htcite0>; <htcite1>).\n\n#### Applying the Scientific Method\n\nKnowledge about the formation of planets is relatively recent. Before <htdate0>, it was believed that planets could not form during the early stages of the universe.\n\nHowever, measurements taken by the Hubble Telescope showed that planets were already forming during the first phases of cosmic history.\n\nThis possibly occurred because the disks that give rise to planets lasted longer in the early universe, creating the necessary conditions for their formation (<htcite2>).\n\nThis discovery reinforces the idea that, in science, knowledge is constantly being updated and expanded.",
